on Robinson -- tA Shropshire Lad -- tKatherine Mansfield -- tFrederick Philip Grove: A Canadian of Canadians -- tThe Poetical Works of Wilfred Campbell -- tThe Poetry of Archibald Lampman0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aRaymond Knister had a strong sense of commitment both to his own career and to literature, particularly Canadian literature. In his ten working years he proved himself a prolific writer with wide-ranging interests. Although his work has appeared in many anthologies of Canadian literature, there remains a great deal of out of print or unpublished material. This volume brings together not only for his more well-known stories but also all his unpublished stories, a few travel pieces, and several examples of his literary criticism. Knister's stories are often strongly regional, and draw on rural Ontario for their setting and characters. Collected together here for the first time is a group of sketches dealing anecdotally with life in a village in southwestern Ontario. Also included are two stories arising from his experiences as a cab driver in Chicago in the 1920s, 'Innocent Man,' and 'Hackman's Night.' His essays focusing on literary matters and the traditions and problems of Canadian literature show a keenly critical mind. The First Day of Spring is an important rediscovery of one of Canada's best writers of the 1920s.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aLITERARY COLLECTIONS / Essays.2bisacsh1 aLochhead, Douglas, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aStevens, Peter.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999z978311049094740uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148758938740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487589387423Coveruhttps://www.deg